{
  "local_port": 50126,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Which are the best website for coding competition?",
  "response": "There are several websites that host coding competitions and challenges, catering to different skill levels and programming languages. Here are some of the best websites for coding competitions:\n\n### 1. **LeetCode**\n   - **Focus:** Algorithms, data structures, and system design.\n   - **Features:** Daily challenges, weekly contests, and interview preparation.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Preparing for technical interviews, especially for FAANG companies.\n\n### 2. **HackerRank**\n   - **Focus:** Algorithms, data structures, artificial intelligence, and more.\n   - **Features:** Challenges, competitions, and company-sponsored hackathons.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Beginners and intermediate coders, as well as job seekers.\n\n### 3. **Codeforces**\n   - **Focus:** Competitive programming, algorithms, and mathematical problems.\n   - **Features:** Regular contests, rating system, and community engagement.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Advanced competitive programmers looking to improve their skills and rankings.\n\n### 4. **TopCoder**\n   - **Focus:** Algorithm, data science, and development challenges.\n   - **Features:** SRMs (Single Round Matches), marathon matches, and crowdsourcing projects.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Competitive programmers and those interested in real-world development challenges.\n\n### 5. **Codewars**\n   - **Focus:** Kata (challenges) that improve coding skills across various languages.\n   - **Features:** Community-driven challenges, ranking system, and gamified learning.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Learning new languages and improving coding skills through gamification.\n\n### 6. **AtCoder**\n   - **Focus:** Competitive programming with contests in Japanese and English.\n   - **Features:** Regular contests (ABC, ARC, AGC), and a rating system.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Japanese-speaking coders and those interested in competitive programming.\n\n### 7. **CodeChef**\n   - **Focus:** Competitive programming, algorithms, and data structures.\n   - **Features:** Long contests, short contests, and cook-offs.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Coders looking for a variety of contests and challenges.\n\n### 8. **Kaggle**\n   - **Focus:** Data science, machine learning, and analytics.\n   - **Features:** Competitions, datasets, and notebooks.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Data scientists and machine learning enthusiasts.\n\n### 9. **Exercism**\n   - **Focus:** Learning and improving coding skills through exercises.\n   - **Features:** Mentored exercises, community feedback, and multiple tracks for different languages.\n   - **Platform:** Web, CLI.\n   - **Best For:** Learners who want structured exercises and mentorship.\n\n### 10. **GeeksforGeeks**\n   - **Focus:** Algorithms, data structures, and coding practice.\n   - **Features:** Coding challenges, contests, and interview preparation.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Beginners and intermediate coders looking for a comprehensive resource.\n\n### 11. **Codeforces Gym**\n   - **Focus:** Practice and training for competitive programming.\n   - **Features:** Virtual contests, problemset, and training sessions.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Competitive programmers who want to practice specific topics or contest formats.\n\n### 12. **Sphere Online Judge (SPOJ)**\n   - **Focus:** Competitive programming and algorithmic challenges.\n   - **Features:** Problemset, challenges, and community-driven content.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Coders who enjoy solving algorithmic problems and participating in challenges.\n\n### 13. **Project Euler**\n   - **Focus:** Mathematical and computational problems.\n   - **Features:** Sequential problems that increase in difficulty.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Those interested in mathematical programming and problem-solving.\n\n### 14. **CodinGame**\n   - **Focus:** Game-based coding challenges.\n   - **Features:** Multiplayer coding games, puzzles, and bots.\n   - **Platform:** Web.\n   - **Best For:** Coder who enjoy gaming and want to learn or improve their skills in a fun way.\n\n### 15. **Dcoder**\n   - **Focus:** Mobile coding challenges and competitions.\n   - **Features:** Coding challenges, competitions, and a mobile IDE.\n   - **Platform:** Mobile (iOS, Android).\n   - **Best For:** Coders who prefer mobile platforms for practice.\n\nEach of these platforms has its own strengths and caters to different aspects of coding and programming. Depending on your goals\u2014whether it\u2019s to improve your skills, prepare for interviews, or compete in programming contests\u2014you can choose the platform that best suits your needs.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
